## Practical Examples

### Example 1: Learning a New Concept

```vim
" Lesson is open on left (read-only)
" Your code is on right

# Reading lesson about loops:
/Loop " Search for "Loop"
5j " Move down to see example
ma " Mark this spot for later

# Switch to right buffer
C-w l
# Start writing loop code

# Need to review? 
C-w h " Back to lesson
'a " Jump to marked concept
" ... review ...
C-w l " Back to code
```

### Example 2: Testing Your Code

```vim
# Code is written, want to compile

:terminal " Open terminal in new buffer
gcc solution.c -o solution && ./solution

# See output, has errors?
# Hit Enter to close terminal, fix code

# Test again?
up up enter " Recall previous command
```

### Example 3: Using Macros to Template

```vim
# You need to create 5 similar functions

qa " Record macro
i/* New function */
Enter
fn func_NAME() {
 
}
Escape
jq " Stop recording

" Now play it 5 times
@a @a @a @a @a " Or just 5@a

# Edit each template with your actual function names
```

